title: For Sale:  MARLIN NO 47  FROM ~1930
postcontent: Nice Marlin no. 47 made from 1930 to 1931.  Marlin made these during the stock market crash of '29 and only gave them out if 4 stock shares of Marlin were purhased.  As I understand these were never put out for public sale.  This is a very old and in very good condition Marlin pump action rifle.  The rifle still cycles 22 LR shells in and out like butter although I've never personally fired it.  However my great grandpa did as well as my grandpa.  The pump stock forend has a crack on one side that apparently my grandpa fixed by putting two wood screws in and one small nail.  I never asked him about it, but looks like they've been there for at least 50 years.  To me it just makes the gun have that much more character.  I believe these were acid dipped like the old Stevens so it has a real nice patena.  Front and rear sights are original and never been broken.  Trigger is real nice and smooth.  It's a tube feeder and shoots .22 short, long and Long Rifle.  The metal buttplate is in excellent condition, tight and is original.  This is a really nice collectable.  I will ship but only to a FFL dealer and buyer pays shipping.   I accept cash, USPS money order or cashier's check.Thanks, Jeff

title: For Sale:  S&W Safety Hammerless 32
location: Land O Lakes, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent: I have a nice condition for it's age and fully functioning and firing Smith and Wesson Saftey Hammerless Revolver for sale. It is the first model and was made in 1890 according to S&W database. It is chambered in 32 S&W and will come with a partial box of Remington ammo with 43 rounds left. Will sell for $280 cash OBO Own a piece of history from the late 1800's!   History of this model from the internet: Smith & Wesson Safety Hammerless New Departure or nicknamed by collectors as the Lemon Squeezer in .32 S&W CTG. History: 32 and 38 Safety Hammerless models The Smith & Wesson 32 and 38 Safety Hammerless models were produced from 1887 (1888 for the 32) to just before World War 2. They were chambered in either .32 S&W or .38 S&W with a five-shot cylinder. They were most often produced with a 2-inch, 3-inch, or 3.5-inch barrels; but some 6" barrelled versions are known to exist. These top-break revolvers were designed for fast reloading and concealed carry as the hammer was internal and would not snag when dragging the revolver from a pocket. They were known as "The New Departure" to reflect the company's new approach to designing revolvers. Minor design changes were made to these revolvers over the years, resulting in several different design models, as termed by collectors. The first model was manufactured between 1887-1902.
